# Java Programming Fundamentals Workshop
Duration: 3.5 hours
Target Audience: Complete beginners to Java programming

## Session Overview
This workshop provides an immersive introduction to Java programming, emphasizing hands-on learning and practical application. The curriculum progresses from basic concepts to more complex programming principles.

## Learning Objectives
By the end of this workshop, participants will be able to:
- Write and execute basic Java programs
- Understand fundamental programming concepts
- Apply object-oriented programming principles
- Use essential Java libraries
- Create simple applications independently

## Detailed Schedule

### 1. Introduction to Java (15 minutes)
#### Content
- Brief history: From Oak to Java
- Platform independence concept
- Java's role in modern software development
- Real-world applications and use cases

#### Activities
- Interactive discussion
- Quick demonstration of "Hello World" program

### 2. Environment Setup (20 minutes)
#### Setup Process
- JDK installation walkthrough
- IDE installation (IntelliJ IDEA Community Edition)
- Project creation and configuration
- First program compilation and execution

#### Troubleshooting Guide
- Common installation issues
- Path variable configuration
- IDE-specific configurations

### 3. Basic Syntax and Structure (30 minutes)
#### Core Concepts
- Data types (primitive vs. reference)
- Variables and constants
- Operators and expressions
- Control structures

#### Code Examples
```java
// Variable declarations
int number = 10;
String text = "Hello Java";

// Control structures
if (number > 5) {
    System.out.println("Number is greater than 5");
} else {
    System.out.println("Number is 5 or less");
}

// Loop structures
for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
    System.out.println("Iteration: " + i);
}
```

### 4. Object-Oriented Programming (45 minutes)
#### Topics Covered
- Classes and objects
- Constructors and methods
- Inheritance principles
- Encapsulation concepts
- Polymorphism examples

#### Practical Exercise
```java
class Animal {
    private String name;

    public Animal(String name) {
        this.name = name;
    }

    public void makeSound() {
        System.out.println("Generic animal sound");
    }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
    public Dog(String name) {
        super(name);
    }

    @Override
    public void makeSound() {
        System.out.println("Woof!");
    }
}
```

### 5. Java Standard Libraries (30 minutes)
#### Essential Libraries
- java.lang package
- Collections framework
- Input/Output operations
- Exception handling

#### Demonstration
```java
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.Scanner;

public class LibraryDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        ArrayList<String> items = new ArrayList<>();
        Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);

        System.out.println("Enter three items:");
        for (int i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
            items.add(scanner.nextLine());
        }

        System.out.println("Your items: " + items);
    }
}
```

### 6. Hands-on Project (40 minutes)
#### Project: Simple Task Manager
Participants will create a basic task management application incorporating:
- Class creation
- Array/ArrayList usage
- User input handling
- Basic error handling

### 7. Wrap-up and Resources (30 minutes)
#### Discussion Points
- Common challenges faced
- Best practices review
- Career opportunities in Java development

#### Additional Resources
- Online documentation
- Practice platforms
- Community forums
- Recommended books

## Workshop Materials
- Presentation slides
- Code examples repository
- Exercise worksheets
- Installation guide
- Troubleshooting checklist

## Assessment Methods
- Interactive coding exercises
- Group discussions
- Final project completion
- Peer review sessions

## Notes for Instructors
- Monitor participant progress closely
- Adjust pace based on group understanding
- Encourage questions and discussion
- Provide individual assistance during exercises
- Document common issues for future sessions
